(24, 27, 10, 'Never abandon a friend--either yours or your father''s. Then in your time of need, you won''t have to ask your relatives for assistance. It is better to go to a neighbor than to a relative who lives far away.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 11, 'My child, how happy I will be if you turn out to be wise! Then I will be able to answer my critics.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 12, 'A prudent person foresees the danger ahead and takes precautions. The simpleton goes blindly on and suffers the consequences.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 13, 'Be sure to get collateral from anyone who guarantees the debt of a stranger. Get a deposit if someone guarantees the debt of an adulterous woman.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 14, 'If you shout a pleasant greeting to your neighbor too early in the morning, it will be counted as a curse!', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 15, 'A nagging wife is as annoying as the constant dripping on a rainy day.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 16, 'Trying to stop her complaints is like trying to stop the wind or hold something with greased hands.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 17, 'As iron sharpens iron, a friend sharpens a friend.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 18, 'Workers who tend a fig tree are allowed to eat its fruit. In the same way, workers who protect their employer''s interests will be rewarded.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 19, 'As a face is reflected in water, so the heart reflects the person.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 20, 'Just as Death and Destruction are never satisfied, so human desire is never satisfied.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 21, 'Fire tests the purity of silver and gold, but a person is tested by being praised.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 22, 'You cannot separate fools from their foolishness, even though you grind them like grain with mortar and pestle.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 23, 'Know the state of your flocks, and put your heart into caring for your herds,', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 24, 'for riches don''t last forever, and the crown might not be secure for the next generation.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 25, 'After the hay is harvested, the new crop appears, and the mountain grasses are gathered in,', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 26, 'your sheep will provide wool for clothing, and your goats will be sold for the price of a field.', 'NLT'),
(24, 27, 27, 'And you will have enough goats'' milk for you, your family, and your servants.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 1, 'The wicked run away when no one is chasing them, but the godly are as bold as lions.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 2, 'When there is moral rot within a nation, its government topples easily. But with wise and knowledgeable leaders, there is stability.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 3, 'A poor person who oppresses the poor is like a pounding rain that destroys the crops.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 4, 'To reject the law is to praise the wicked; to obey the law is to fight them.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 5, 'Evil people don''t understand justice, but those who follow the LORD understand completely.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 6, 'It is better to be poor and honest than rich and crooked.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 7, 'Young people who obey the law are wise; those who seek out worthless companions bring shame to their parents.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 8, 'A person who makes money by charging interest will lose it. It will end up in the hands of someone who is kind to the poor.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 9, 'The prayers of a person who ignores the law are despised.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 10, 'Those who lead the upright into sin will fall into their own trap, but the honest will inherit good things.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 11, 'Rich people picture themselves as wise, but their real poverty is evident to the poor.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 12, 'When the godly succeed, everyone is glad. When the wicked take charge, people go into hiding.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 13, 'People who cover over their sins will not prosper. But if they confess and forsake them, they will receive mercy.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 14, 'Blessed are those who have a tender conscience, but the stubborn are headed for serious trouble.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 15, 'A wicked ruler is as dangerous to the poor as a lion or bear attacking them.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 16, 'Only a stupid prince will oppress his people, but a king will have a long reign if he hates dishonesty and bribes.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 17, 'A murderer''s tormented conscience will drive him into the grave. Don''t protect him!', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 18, 'The honest will be rescued from harm, but those who are crooked will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 19, 'Hard workers have plenty of food; playing around brings poverty.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 20, 'The trustworthy will get a rich reward. But the person who wants to get rich quick will only get into trouble.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 21, 'Showing partiality is never good, yet some will do wrong for something as small as a piece of bread.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 22, 'A greedy person tries to get rich quick, but it only leads to poverty.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 23, 'In the end, people appreciate frankness more than flattery.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 24, 'Robbing your parents and then saying, "What''s wrong with that?" is as serious as committing murder.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 25, 'Greed causes fighting; trusting the LORD leads to prosperity.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 26, 'Trusting oneself is foolish, but those who walk in wisdom are safe.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 27, 'Whoever gives to the poor will lack nothing. But a curse will come upon those who close their eyes to poverty.', 'NLT'),
(24, 28, 28, 'When the wicked take charge, people hide. When the wicked meet disaster, the godly multiply.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 1, 'Whoever stubbornly refuses to accept criticism will suddenly be broken beyond repair.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 2, 'When the godly are in authority, the people rejoice. But when the wicked are in power, they groan.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 3, 'The man who loves wisdom brings joy to his father, but if he hangs around with prostitutes, his wealth is wasted.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 4, 'A just king gives stability to his nation, but one who demands bribes destroys it.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 5, 'To flatter people is to lay a trap for their feet.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 6, 'Evil people are trapped by sin, but the righteous escape, shouting for joy.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 7, 'The godly know the rights of the poor; the wicked don''t care to know.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 8, 'Mockers can get a whole town agitated, but those who are wise will calm anger.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 9, 'If a wise person takes a fool to court, there will be ranting and ridicule but no satisfaction.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 10, 'The bloodthirsty hate the honest, but the upright seek out the honest.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 11, 'A fool gives full vent to anger, but a wise person quietly holds it back.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 12, 'If a ruler honors liars, all his advisers will be wicked.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 13, 'The poor and the oppressor have this in common--the LORD gives light to the eyes of both.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 14, 'A king who is fair to the poor will have a long reign.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 15, 'To discipline and reprimand a child produces wisdom, but a mother is disgraced by an undisciplined child.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 16, 'When the wicked are in authority, sin increases. But the godly will live to see the tyrant''s downfall.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 17, 'Discipline your children, and they will give you happiness and peace of mind.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 18, 'When people do not accept divine guidance, they run wild. But whoever obeys the law is happy.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 19, 'For a servant, mere words are not enough--discipline is needed. For the words may be understood, but they are not heeded.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 20, 'There is more hope for a fool than for someone who speaks without thinking.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 21, 'A servant who is pampered from childhood will later become a rebel.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 22, 'A hot-tempered person starts fights and gets into all kinds of sin.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 23, 'Pride ends in humiliation, while humility brings honor.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 24, 'If you assist a thief, you are only hurting yourself. You will be punished if you report the crime, but you will be cursed if you don''t.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 25, 'Fearing people is a dangerous trap, but to trust the LORD means safety.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 26, 'Many seek the ruler''s favor, but justice comes from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(24, 29, 27, 'The godly despise the wicked; the wicked despise the godly.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 1, 'The message of Agur son of Jakeh. An oracle. I am weary, O God; I am weary and worn out, O God.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 2, 'I am too ignorant to be human, and I lack common sense.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 3, 'I have not mastered human wisdom, nor do I know the Holy One.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 4, 'Who but God goes up to heaven and comes back down? Who holds the wind in his fists? Who wraps up the oceans in his cloak? Who has created the whole wide world? What is his name--and his son''s name? Tell me if you know!', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 5, 'Every word of God proves true. He defends all who come to him for protection.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 6, 'Do not add to his words, or he may rebuke you, and you will be found a liar.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 7, 'O God, I beg two favors from you before I die.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 8, 'First, help me never to tell a lie. Second, give me neither poverty nor riches! Give me just enough to satisfy my needs.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 9, 'For if I grow rich, I may deny you and say, "Who is the LORD?" And if I am too poor, I may steal and thus insult God''s holy name.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 10, 'Never slander a person to his employer. If you do, the person will curse you, and you will pay for it.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 11, 'Some people curse their father and do not thank their mother.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 12, 'They feel pure, but they are filthy and unwashed.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 13, 'They are proud beyond description and disdainful.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 14, 'They devour the poor with teeth as sharp as swords or knives. They destroy the needy from the face of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 15, 'The leech has two suckers that cry out, "More, more!" There are three other things--no, four!--that are never satisfied:', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 16, 'the grave, the barren womb, the thirsty desert, the blazing fire.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 17, 'The eye that mocks a father and despises a mother will be plucked out by ravens of the valley and eaten by vultures.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 18, 'There are three things that amaze me--no, four things I do not understand:', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 19, 'how an eagle glides through the sky, how a snake slithers on a rock, how a ship navigates the ocean, how a man loves a woman.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 20, 'Equally amazing is how an adulterous woman can satisfy her sexual appetite, shrug her shoulders, and then say, "What''s wrong with that?"', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 21, 'There are three things that make the earth tremble--no, four it cannot endure:', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 22, 'a slave who becomes a king, an overbearing fool who prospers,', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 23, 'a bitter woman who finally gets a husband, a servant girl who supplants her mistress.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 24, 'There are four things on earth that are small but unusually wise:', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 25, 'Ants--they aren''t strong, but they store up food for the winter.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 26, 'Rock badgers--they aren''t powerful, but they make their homes among the rocky cliffs.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 27, 'Locusts--they have no king, but they march like an army in ranks.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 28, 'Lizards--they are easy to catch, but they are found even in kings'' palaces.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 29, 'There are three stately monarchs on the earth--no, four:', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 30, 'the lion, king of animals, who won''t turn aside for anything,', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 31, 'the strutting rooster, the male goat, a king as he leads his army.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 32, 'If you have been a fool by being proud or plotting evil, don''t brag about it--cover your mouth with your hand in shame.', 'NLT'),
(24, 30, 33, 'As the beating of cream yields butter, and a blow to the nose causes bleeding, so anger causes quarrels.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 1, 'These are the sayings of King Lemuel, an oracle that his mother taught him.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 2, 'O my son, O son of my womb, O son of my promises,', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 3, 'do not spend your strength on women, on those who ruin kings.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 4, 'And it is not for kings, O Lemuel, to guzzle wine. Rulers should not crave liquor.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 5, 'For if they drink, they may forget their duties and be unable to give justice to those who are oppressed.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 6, 'Liquor is for the dying, and wine for those in deep depression.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 7, 'Let them drink to forget their poverty and remember their troubles no more.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 8, 'Speak up for those who cannot speak for themselves; ensure justice for those who are perishing.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 9, 'Yes, speak up for the poor and helpless, and see that they get justice.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 10, 'Who can find a virtuous and capable wife? She is worth more than precious rubies.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 11, 'Her husband can trust her, and she will greatly enrich his life.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 12, 'She will not hinder him but help him all her life.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 13, 'She finds wool and flax and busily spins it.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 14, 'She is like a merchant''s ship; she brings her food from afar.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 15, 'She gets up before dawn to prepare breakfast for her household and plan the day''s work for her servant girls.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 16, 'She goes out to inspect a field and buys it; with her earnings she plants a vineyard.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 17, 'She is energetic and strong, a hard worker.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 18, 'She watches for bargains; her lights burn late into the night.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 19, 'Her hands are busy spinning thread, her fingers twisting fiber.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 20, 'She extends a helping hand to the poor and opens her arms to the needy.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 21, 'She has no fear of winter for her household because all of them have warm clothes.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 22, 'She quilts her own bedspreads. She dresses like royalty in gowns of finest cloth.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 23, 'Her husband is well known, for he sits in the council meeting with the other civic leaders.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 24, 'She makes belted linen garments and sashes to sell to the merchants.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 25, 'She is clothed with strength and dignity, and she laughs with no fear of the future.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 26, 'When she speaks, her words are wise, and kindness is the rule when she gives instructions.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 27, 'She carefully watches all that goes on in her household and does not have to bear the consequences of laziness.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 28, 'Her children stand and bless her. Her husband praises her:', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 29, '"There are many virtuous and capable women in the world, but you surpass them all!"', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 30, 'Charm is deceptive, and beauty does not last; but a woman who fears the LORD will be greatly praised.', 'NLT'),
(24, 31, 31, 'Reward her for all she has done. Let her deeds publicly declare her praise.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 1, 'These are the words of the Teacher, King David''s son, who ruled in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 2, '"Everything is meaningless," says the Teacher, "utterly meaningless!"', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 3, 'What do people get for all their hard work?', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 4, 'Generations come and go, but nothing really changes.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 5, 'The sun rises and sets and hurries around to rise again.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 6, 'The wind blows south and north, here and there, twisting back and forth, getting nowhere.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 7, 'The rivers run into the sea, but the sea is never full. Then the water returns again to the rivers and flows again to the sea.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 8, 'Everything is so weary and tiresome! No matter how much we see, we are never satisfied. No matter how much we hear, we are not content.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 9, 'History merely repeats itself. It has all been done before. Nothing under the sun is truly new.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 10, 'What can you point to that is new? How do you know it didn''t already exist long ago?', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 11, 'We don''t remember what happened in those former times. And in future generations, no one will remember what we are doing now.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 12, 'I, the Teacher, was king of Israel, and I lived in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 13, 'I devoted myself to search for understanding and to explore by wisdom everything being done in the world. I soon discovered that God has dealt a tragic existence to the human race.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 14, 'Everything under the sun is meaningless, like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 15, 'What is wrong cannot be righted. What is missing cannot be recovered.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 16, 'I said to myself, "Look, I am wiser than any of the kings who ruled in Jerusalem before me. I have greater wisdom and knowledge than any of them."', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 17, 'So I worked hard to distinguish wisdom from foolishness. But now I realize that even this was like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 1, 18, 'For the greater my wisdom, the greater my grief. To increase knowledge only increases sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 1, 'I said to myself, "Come now, let''s give pleasure a try. Let''s look for the `good things'' in life." But I found that this, too, was meaningless.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 2, '"It is silly to be laughing all the time," I said. "What good does it do to seek only pleasure?"', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 3, 'After much thought, I decided to cheer myself with wine. While still seeking wisdom, I clutched at foolishness. In this way, I hoped to experience the only happiness most people find during their brief life in this world.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 4, 'I also tried to find meaning by building huge homes for myself and by planting beautiful vineyards.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 5, 'I made gardens and parks, filling them with all kinds of fruit trees.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 6, 'I built reservoirs to collect the water to irrigate my many flourishing groves.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 7, 'I bought slaves, both men and women, and others were born into my household. I also owned great herds and flocks, more than any of the kings who lived in Jerusalem before me.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 8, 'I collected great sums of silver and gold, the treasure of many kings and provinces. I hired wonderful singers, both men and women, and had many beautiful concubines. I had everything a man could desire!', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 9, 'So I became greater than any of the kings who ruled in Jerusalem before me. And with it all, I remained clear-eyed so that I could evaluate all these things.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 10, 'Anything I wanted, I took. I did not restrain myself from any joy. I even found great pleasure in hard work, an additional reward for all my labors.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 11, 'But as I looked at everything I had worked so hard to accomplish, it was all so meaningless. It was like chasing the wind. There was nothing really worthwhile anywhere.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 12, 'So I decided to compare wisdom and folly, and anyone else would come to the same conclusions I did.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 13, 'Wisdom is of more value than foolishness, just as light is better than darkness.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 14, 'For the wise person sees, while the fool is blind. Yet I saw that wise and foolish people share the same fate.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 15, 'Both of them die. Just as the fool will die, so will I. So of what value is all my wisdom? Then I said to myself, "This is all so meaningless!"', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 16, 'For the wise person and the fool both die, and in the days to come, both will be forgotten.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 17, 'So now I hate life because everything done here under the sun is so irrational. Everything is meaningless, like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 18, 'I am disgusted that I must leave the fruits of my hard work to others.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 19, 'And who can tell whether my successors will be wise or foolish? And yet they will control everything I have gained by my skill and hard work. How meaningless!', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 20, 'So I turned in despair from hard work. It was not the answer to my search for satisfaction in this life.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 21, 'For though I do my work with wisdom, knowledge, and skill, I must leave everything I gain to people who haven''t worked to earn it. This is not only foolish but highly unfair.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 22, 'So what do people get for all their hard work?', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 23, 'Their days of labor are filled with pain and grief; even at night they cannot rest. It is all utterly meaningless.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 24, 'So I decided there is nothing better than to enjoy food and drink and to find satisfaction in work. Then I realized that this pleasure is from the hand of God.', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 25, 'For who can eat or enjoy anything apart from him?', 'NLT'),
(25, 2, 26, 'God gives wisdom, knowledge, and joy to those who please him. But if a sinner becomes wealthy, God takes the wealth away and gives it to those who please him. Even this, however, is meaningless, like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 1, '1 There is a time for everything, a season for every activity under heaven.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 2, 'A time to be born and a time to die. A time to plant and a time to harvest.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 3, 'A time to kill and a time to heal. A time to tear down and a time to rebuild.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 4, 'A time to cry and a time to laugh. A time to grieve and a time to dance.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 5, 'A time to scatter stones and a time to gather stones. A time to embrace and a time to turn away.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 6, 'A time to search and a time to lose. A time to keep and a time to throw away.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 7, 'A time to tear and a time to mend. A time to be quiet and a time to speak up.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 8, 'A time to love and a time to hate. A time for war and a time for peace.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 9, 'What do people really get for all their hard work?', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 10, 'I have thought about this in connection with the various kinds of work God has given people to do.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 11, 'God has made everything beautiful for its own time. He has planted eternity in the human heart, but even so, people cannot see the whole scope of God''s work from beginning to end.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 12, 'So I concluded that there is nothing better for people than to be happy and to enjoy themselves as long as they can.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 13, 'And people should eat and drink and enjoy the fruits of their labor, for these are gifts from God.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 14, 'And I know that whatever God does is final. Nothing can be added to it or taken from it. God''s purpose in this is that people should fear him.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 15, 'Whatever exists today and whatever will exist in the future has already existed in the past. For God calls each event back in its turn.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 16, 'I also noticed that throughout the world there is evil in the courtroom. Yes, even the courts of law are corrupt!', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 17, 'I said to myself, "In due season God will judge everyone, both good and bad, for all their deeds."', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 18, 'Then I realized that God allows people to continue in their sinful ways so he can test them. That way, they can see for themselves that they are no better than animals.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 19, 'For humans and animals both breathe the same air, and both die. So people have no real advantage over the animals. How meaningless!', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 20, 'Both go to the same place--the dust from which they came and to which they must return.', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 21, 'For who can prove that the human spirit goes upward and the spirit of animals goes downward into the earth?', 'NLT'),
(25, 3, 22, 'So I saw that there is nothing better for people than to be happy in their work. That is why they are here! No one will bring them back from death to enjoy life in the future.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 1, 'Again I observed all the oppression that takes place in our world. I saw the tears of the oppressed, with no one to comfort them. The oppressors have great power, and the victims are helpless.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 2, 'So I concluded that the dead are better off than the living.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 3, 'And most fortunate of all are those who were never born. For they have never seen all the evil that is done in our world.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 4, 'Then I observed that most people are motivated to success by their envy of their neighbors. But this, too, is meaningless, like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 5, 'Foolish people refuse to work and almost starve.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 6, 'They feel it is better to be lazy and barely survive than to work hard, especially when in the long run everything is so futile.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 7, 'I observed yet another example of meaninglessness in our world.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 8, 'This is the case of a man who is all alone, without a child or a brother, yet who works hard to gain as much wealth as he can. But then he asks himself, "Who am I working for? Why am I giving up so much pleasure now?" It is all so meaningless and depressing.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 9, 'Two people can accomplish more than twice as much as one; they get a better return for their labor.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 10, 'If one person falls, the other can reach out and help. But people who are alone when they fall are in real trouble.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 11, 'And on a cold night, two under the same blanket can gain warmth from each other. But how can one be warm alone?', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 12, 'A person standing alone can be attacked and defeated, but two can stand back-to-back and conquer. Three are even better, for a triple-braided cord is not easily broken.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 13, 'It is better to be a poor but wise youth than to be an old and foolish king who refuses all advice.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 14, 'Such a youth could come from prison and succeed. He might even become king, though he was born in poverty.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 15, 'Everyone is eager to help such a youth, even to help him take the throne.', 'NLT'),
(25, 4, 16, 'He might become the leader of millions and be very popular. But then the next generation grows up and rejects him! So again, it is all meaningless, like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 1, 'As you enter the house of God, keep your ears open and your mouth shut! Don''t be a fool who doesn''t realize that mindless offerings to God are evil.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 2, 'And don''t make rash promises to God, for he is in heaven, and you are only here on earth. So let your words be few.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 3, 'Just as being too busy gives you nightmares, being a fool makes you a blabbermouth.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 4, 'So when you make a promise to God, don''t delay in following through, for God takes no pleasure in fools. Keep all the promises you make to him.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 5, 'It is better to say nothing than to promise something that you don''t follow through on.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 6, 'In such cases, your mouth is making you sin. And don''t defend yourself by telling the Temple messenger that the promise you made was a mistake. That would make God angry, and he might wipe out everything you have achieved.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 7, 'Dreaming all the time instead of working is foolishness. And there is ruin in a flood of empty words. Fear God instead.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 8, 'If you see a poor person being oppressed by the powerful and justice being miscarried throughout the land, don''t be surprised! For every official is under orders from higher up, and matters of justice only get lost in red tape and bureaucracy.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 9, 'Even the king milks the land for his own profit!', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 10, 'Those who love money will never have enough. How absurd to think that wealth brings true happiness!', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 11, 'The more you have, the more people come to help you spend it. So what is the advantage of wealth--except perhaps to watch it run through your fingers!', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 12, 'People who work hard sleep well, whether they eat little or much. But the rich are always worrying and seldom get a good night''s sleep.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 13, 'There is another serious problem I have seen in the world. Riches are sometimes hoarded to the harm of the saver,', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 14, 'or they are put into risky investments that turn sour, and everything is lost. In the end, there is nothing left to pass on to one''s children.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 15, 'People who live only for wealth come to the end of their lives as naked and empty-handed as on the day they were born.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 16, 'And this, too, is a very serious problem. As people come into this world, so they depart. All their hard work is for nothing. They have been working for the wind, and everything will be swept away.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 17, 'Throughout their lives, they live under a cloud--frustrated, discouraged, and angry.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 18, 'Even so, I have noticed one thing, at least, that is good. It is good for people to eat well, drink a good glass of wine, and enjoy their work--whatever they do under the sun--for however long God lets them live.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 19, 'And it is a good thing to receive wealth from God and the good health to enjoy it. To enjoy your work and accept your lot in life--that is indeed a gift from God.', 'NLT'),
(25, 5, 20, 'People who do this rarely look with sorrow on the past, for God has given them reasons for joy.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 1, 'There is another serious tragedy I have seen in our world.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 2, 'God gives great wealth and honor to some people and gives them everything they could ever want, but then he doesn''t give them the health to enjoy it. They die, and others get it all! This is meaningless--a sickening tragedy.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 3, 'A man might have a hundred children and live to be very old. But if he finds no satisfaction in life and in the end does not even get a decent burial, I say he would have been better off born dead.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 4, 'I realize that his birth would have been meaningless and ended in darkness. He wouldn''t even have had a name,', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 5, 'and he would never have seen the sun or known of its existence. Yet he would have had more peace than he has in growing up to be an unhappy man.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 6, 'He might live a thousand years twice over but not find contentment. And since he must die like everyone else--well, what''s the use?', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 7, 'All people spend their lives scratching for food, but they never seem to have enough.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 8, 'Considering this, do wise people really have any advantage over fools? Do poor people gain anything by being wise and knowing how to act in front of others?', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 9, 'Enjoy what you have rather than desiring what you don''t have. Just dreaming about nice things is meaningless; it is like chasing the wind.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 10, 'Everything has already been decided. It was known long ago what each person would be. So there''s no use arguing with God about your destiny.', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 11, 'The more words you speak, the less they mean. So why overdo it?', 'NLT'),
(25, 6, 12, 'In the few days of our empty lives, who knows how our days can best be spent? And who can tell what will happen in the future after we are gone?', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 1, 'A good reputation is more valuable than the most expensive perfume. In the same way, the day you die is better than the day you are born.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 2, 'It is better to spend your time at funerals than at festivals. For you are going to die, and you should think about it while there is still time.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 3, 'Sorrow is better than laughter, for sadness has a refining influence on us.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 4, 'A wise person thinks much about death, while the fool thinks only about having a good time now.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 5, 'It is better to be criticized by a wise person than to be praised by a fool!', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 6, 'Indeed, a fool''s laughter is quickly gone, like thorns crackling in a fire. This also is meaningless.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 7, 'Extortion turns wise people into fools, and bribes corrupt the heart.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 8, 'Finishing is better than starting. Patience is better than pride.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 9, 'Don''t be quick-tempered, for anger is the friend of fools.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 10, 'Don''t long for "the good old days," for you don''t know whether they were any better than today.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 11, 'Being wise is as good as being rich; in fact, it is better.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 12, 'Wisdom or money can get you almost anything, but it''s important to know that only wisdom can save your life.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 13, 'Notice the way God does things; then fall into line. Don''t fight the ways of God, for who can straighten out what he has made crooked?', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 14, 'Enjoy prosperity while you can. But when hard times strike, realize that both come from God. That way you will realize that nothing is certain in this life.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 15, 'In this meaningless life, I have seen everything, including the fact that some good people die young and some wicked people live on and on.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 16, 'So don''t be too good or too wise! Why destroy yourself?', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 17, 'On the other hand, don''t be too wicked either--don''t be a fool! Why should you die before your time?', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 18, 'So try to walk a middle course--but those who fear God will succeed either way.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 19, 'A wise person is stronger than the ten leading citizens of a town!', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 20, 'There is not a single person in all the earth who is always good and never sins.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 21, 'Don''t eavesdrop on others--you may hear your servant laughing at you.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 22, 'For you know how often you yourself have laughed at others.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 23, 'All along I have tried my best to let wisdom guide my thoughts and actions. I said to myself, "I am determined to be wise." But it didn''t really work.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 24, 'Wisdom is always distant and very difficult to find.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 25, 'I searched everywhere, determined to find wisdom and to understand the reason for things. I was determined to prove to myself that wickedness is stupid and that foolishness is madness.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 26, 'I discovered that a seductive woman is more bitter than death. Her passion is a trap, and her soft hands will bind you. Those who please God will escape from her, but sinners will be caught in her snare.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 27, '"This is my conclusion," says the Teacher. "I came to this result after looking into the matter from every possible angle.', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 28, 'Just one out of every thousand men I interviewed can be said to be upright, but not one woman!', 'NLT'),
(25, 7, 29, 'I discovered that God created people to be upright, but they have each turned to follow their own downward path."', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 1, 'How wonderful to be wise, to be able to analyze and interpret things. Wisdom lights up a person''s face, softening its hardness.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 2, 'Obey the king because you have vowed before God to do this.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 3, 'Don''t try to avoid doing your duty, and don''t take a stand with those who plot evil. For the king will punish those who disobey him.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 4, 'The king''s command is backed by great power. No one can resist or question it.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 5, 'Those who obey him will not be punished. Those who are wise will find a time and a way to do what is right.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 6, 'Yes, there is a time and a way for everything, even as people''s troubles lie heavily upon them.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 7, 'Indeed, how can people avoid what they don''t know is going to happen?', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 8, 'None of us can hold back our spirit from departing. None of us has the power to prevent the day of our death. There is no escaping that obligation, that dark battle. And in the face of death, wickedness will certainly not rescue those who practice it.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 9, 'I have thought deeply about all that goes on here in the world, where people have the power to hurt each other.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 10, 'I have seen wicked people buried with honor. How strange that they were the very ones who frequented the Temple and are praised in the very city where they committed their crimes!', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 11, 'When a crime is not punished, people feel it is safe to do wrong.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 12, 'But even though a person sins a hundred times and still lives a long time, I know that those who fear God will be better off.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 13, 'The wicked will never live long, good lives, for they do not fear God. Their days will never grow long like the evening shadows.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 14, 'And this is not all that is meaningless in our world. In this life, good people are often treated as though they were wicked, and wicked people are often treated as though they were good. This is so meaningless!', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 15, 'So I recommend having fun, because there is nothing better for people to do in this world than to eat, drink, and enjoy life. That way they will experience some happiness along with all the hard work God gives them.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 16, 'In my search for wisdom, I tried to observe everything that goes on all across the earth. I discovered that there is ceaseless activity, day and night.', 'NLT'),
(25, 8, 17, 'This reminded me that no one can discover everything God has created in our world, no matter how hard they work at it. Not even the wisest people know everything, even if they say they do.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 1, 'This, too, I carefully explored: Even though the actions of godly and wise people are in God''s hands, no one knows whether or not God will show them favor in this life.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 2, 'The same destiny ultimately awaits everyone, whether they are righteous or wicked, good or bad, ceremonially clean or unclean, religious or irreligious. Good people receive the same treatment as sinners, and people who take oaths are treated like people who don''t.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 3, 'It seems so tragic that one fate comes to all. That is why people are not more careful to be good. Instead, they choose their own mad course, for they have no hope. There is nothing ahead but death anyway.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 4, 'There is hope only for the living. For as they say, "It is better to be a live dog than a dead lion!"', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 5, 'The living at least know they will die, but the dead know nothing. They have no further reward, nor are they remembered.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 6, 'Whatever they did in their lifetime--loving, hating, envying--is all long gone. They no longer have a part in anything here on earth.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 7, 'So go ahead. Eat your food and drink your wine with a happy heart, for God approves of this!', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 8, 'Wear fine clothes, with a dash of cologne!', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 9, 'Live happily with the woman you love through all the meaningless days of life that God has given you in this world. The wife God gives you is your reward for all your earthly toil.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 10, 'Whatever you do, do well. For when you go to the grave, there will be no work or planning or knowledge or wisdom.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 11, 'I have observed something else in this world of ours. The fastest runner doesn''t always win the race, and the strongest warrior doesn''t always win the battle. The wise are often poor, and the skillful are not necessarily wealthy. And those who are educated don''t always lead successful lives. It is all decided by chance, by being at the right place at the right time.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 12, 'People can never predict when hard times might come. Like fish in a net or birds in a snare, people are often caught by sudden tragedy.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 13, 'Here is another bit of wisdom that has impressed me as I have watched the way our world works.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 14, 'There was a small town with only a few people living in it, and a great king came with his army and besieged it.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 15, 'There was a poor, wise man living there who knew how to save the town, and so it was rescued. But afterward no one thought any more about him.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 16, 'Then I realized that though wisdom is better than strength, those who are wise will be despised if they are poor. What they say will not be appreciated for long.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 17, 'But even so, the quiet words of a wise person are better than the shouts of a foolish king.', 'NLT'),
(25, 9, 18, 'A wise person can overcome weapons of war, but one sinner can destroy much that is good.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 1, 'Dead flies will cause even a bottle of perfume to stink! Yes, an ounce of foolishness can outweigh a pound of wisdom and honor.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 2, 'The hearts of the wise lead them to do right, and the hearts of the foolish lead them to do evil.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 3, 'You can identify fools just by the way they walk down the street!', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 4, 'If your boss is angry with you, don''t quit! A quiet spirit can overcome even great mistakes.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 5, 'There is another evil I have seen as I have watched the world go by. Kings and rulers make a grave mistake', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 6, 'if they give foolish people great authority, and if they fail to give people of proven worth their rightful place of dignity.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 7, 'I have even seen servants riding like princes--and princes walking like servants.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 8, 'When you dig a well, you may fall in. When you demolish an old wall, you could be bitten by a snake.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 9, 'When you work in a quarry, stones might fall and crush you! When you chop wood, there is danger with each stroke of your ax! Such are the risks of life.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 10, 'Since a dull ax requires great strength, sharpen the blade. That''s the value of wisdom; it helps you succeed.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 11, 'It does no good to charm a snake after it has bitten you.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 12, 'It is pleasant to listen to wise words, but the speech of fools brings them to ruin.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 13, 'Since fools base their thoughts on foolish premises, their conclusions will be wicked madness.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 14, 'Foolish people claim to know all about the future and tell everyone the details! But who can really know what is going to happen?', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 15, 'Fools are so exhausted by a little work that they have no strength for even the simplest tasks.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 16, 'Destruction is certain for the land whose king is a child and whose leaders feast in the morning.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 17, 'Happy is the land whose king is a nobleman and whose leaders feast only to gain strength for their work, not to get drunk.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 18, 'Laziness lets the roof leak, and soon the rafters begin to rot.', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 19, 'A party gives laughter, and wine gives happiness, and money gives everything!', 'NLT'),
(25, 10, 20, 'Never make light of the king, even in your thoughts. And don''t make fun of a rich man, either. A little bird may tell them what you have said.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 1, 'Give generously, for your gifts will return to you later.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 2, 'Divide your gifts among many, for you do not know what risks might lie ahead.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 3, 'When the clouds are heavy, the rains come down. When a tree falls, whether south or north, there it lies.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 4, 'If you wait for perfect conditions, you will never get anything done.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 5, 'God''s ways are as hard to discern as the pathways of the wind, and as mysterious as a tiny baby being formed in a mother''s womb.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 6, 'Be sure to stay busy and plant a variety of crops, for you never know which will grow--perhaps they all will.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 7, 'Light is sweet; it''s wonderful to see the sun!', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 8, 'When people live to be very old, let them rejoice in every day of life. But let them also remember that the dark days will be many. Everything still to come is meaningless.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 9, 'Young man, it''s wonderful to be young! Enjoy every minute of it. Do everything you want to do; take it all in. But remember that you must give an account to God for everything you do.', 'NLT'),
(25, 11, 10, 'So banish grief and pain, but remember that youth, with a whole life before it, still faces the threat of meaninglessness.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 1, 'Don''t let the excitement of youth cause you to forget your Creator. Honor him in your youth before you grow old and no longer enjoy living.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 2, 'It will be too late then to remember him, when the light of the sun and moon and stars is dim to your old eyes, and there is no silver lining left among the clouds.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 3, 'Your limbs will tremble with age, and your strong legs will grow weak. Your teeth will be too few to do their work, and you will be blind, too.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 4, 'And when your teeth are gone, keep your lips tightly closed when you eat! Even the chirping of birds will wake you up. But you yourself will be deaf and tuneless, with a quavering voice.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 5, 'You will be afraid of heights and of falling, white-haired and withered, dragging along without any sexual desire. You will be standing at death''s door. And as you near your everlasting home, the mourners will walk along the streets.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 6, 'Yes, remember your Creator now while you are young, before the silver cord of life snaps and the golden bowl is broken. Don''t wait until the water jar is smashed at the spring and the pulley is broken at the well.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 7, 'For then the dust will return to the earth, and the spirit will return to God who gave it.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 8, '"All is meaningless," says the Teacher, "utterly meaningless."', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 9, 'Because the Teacher was wise, he taught the people everything he knew. He collected proverbs and classified them.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 10, 'Indeed, the Teacher taught the plain truth, and he did so in an interesting way.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 11, 'A wise teacher''s words spur students to action and emphasize important truths. The collected sayings of the wise are like guidance from a shepherd.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 12, 'But, my child, be warned: There is no end of opinions ready to be expressed. Studying them can go on forever and become very exhausting!', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 13, 'Here is my final conclusion: Fear God and obey his commands, for this is the duty of every person.', 'NLT'),
(25, 12, 14, 'God will judge us for everything we do, including every secret thing, whether good or bad.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 1, 'This is Solomon''s song of songs, more wonderful than any other.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 2, 'Kiss me again and again, for your love is sweeter than wine.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 3, 'How fragrant your cologne, and how pleasing your name! No wonder all the young women love you!', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 4, 'Take me with you. Come, lets run! Bring me into your bedroom, O my king. How happy we are for him! We praise his love even more than wine. How right that the young women love you!', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 5, '"I am dark and beautiful, O women of Jerusalem, tanned as the dark tents of Kedar. Yes, even as the tents of Solomon!', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 6, '"Don''t look down on me, you fair city girls, just because my complexion is so dark. The sun has burned my skin. My brothers were angry with me and sent me out to tend the vineyards in the hot sun. Now see what it has done to me!', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 7, '"Tell me, O my love, where are you leading your flock today? Where will you rest your sheep at noon? For why should I wander like a prostitute among the flocks of your companions?"', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 8, 'If you dont know, O most beautiful woman, follow the trail of my flock to the shepherds tents, and there feed your young goats.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 9, 'What a lovely filly you are, my beloved one!', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 10, 'How lovely are your cheeks, with your earrings setting them afire! How stately is your neck, accented with a long string of jewels.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 11, 'We will make earrings of gold for you and beads of silver.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 12, 'The king is lying on his couch, enchanted by the fragrance of my perfume.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 13, 'My lover is like a sachet of myrrh lying between my breasts.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 14, 'He is like a bouquet of flowers in the gardens of En-gedi.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 15, 'How beautiful you are, my beloved, how beautiful! Your eyes are soft like doves.', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 16, 'What a lovely, pleasant sight you are, my love, as we lie here on the grass,', 'NLT'),
(26, 1, 17, 'shaded by cedar trees and spreading firs.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 1, 'I am the rose of Sharon, the lily of the valley.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 2, 'Yes, compared to other women, my beloved is like a lily among thorns.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 3, 'And compared to other youths, my lover is like the finest apple tree in the orchard. I am seated in his delightful shade, and his fruit is delicious to eat.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 4, 'He brings me to the banquet hall, so everyone can see how much he loves me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 5, 'Oh, feed me with your love--your `raisins and your `apples--for I am utterly lovesick!', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 6, 'His left hand is under my head, and his right hand embraces me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 7, '"Promise me, O women of Jerusalem, by the swift gazelles and the deer of the wild, not to awaken love until the time is right.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 8, '"Ah, I hear him--my lover! Here he comes, leaping on the mountains and bounding over the hills.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 9, 'My lover is like a swift gazelle or a young deer. Look, there he is behind the wall! Now he is looking in through the window, gazing into the room.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 10, '"My lover said to me, `Rise up, my beloved, my fair one, and come away.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 11, 'For the winter is past, and the rain is over and gone.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 12, 'The flowers are springing up, and the time of singing birds has come, even the cooing of turtledoves.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 13, 'The fig trees are budding, and the grapevines are in blossom. How delicious they smell! Yes, spring is here! Arise, my beloved, my fair one, and come away.''"', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 14, 'My dove is hiding behind some rocks, behind an outcrop on the cliff. Let me see you; let me hear your voice. For your voice is pleasant, and you are lovely.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 15, 'Quick! Catch all the little foxes before they ruin the vineyard of your love, for the grapevines are all in blossom.', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 16, 'My lover is mine, and I am his. He feeds among the lilies!', 'NLT'),
(26, 2, 17, 'Before the dawn comes and the shadows flee away, come back to me, my love. Run like a gazelle or a young stag on the rugged mountains.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 1, 'One night as I lay in bed, I yearned deeply for my lover, but he did not come.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 2, 'So I said to myself, `I will get up now and roam the city, searching for him in all its streets and squares. But my search was in vain.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 3, 'The watchmen stopped me as they made their rounds, and I said to them, `Have you seen him anywhere, this one I love so much?', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 4, 'A little while later I found him and held him. I didnt let him go until I had brought him to my childhood home, into my mothers bedroom, where I had been conceived.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 5, '"Promise me, O women of Jerusalem, by the swift gazelles and the deer of the wild, not to awaken love until the time is right. "', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 6, 'Who is this sweeping in from the deserts like a cloud of smoke along the ground? Who is it that smells of myrrh and frankincense and every other spice?', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 7, 'Look, it is Solomons carriage, with sixty of Israels mightiest men surrounding it.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 8, 'They are all skilled swordsmen and experienced warriors. Each one wears a sword on his thigh, ready to defend the king against an attack during the night.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 9, '"King Solomon has built a carriage for himself from wood imported from Lebanon''s forests.', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 10, 'Its posts are of silver, its canopy is gold, and its seat is upholstered in purple cloth. Its interior was a gift of love from the young women of Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(26, 3, 11, 'Go out to look upon King Solomon, O young women of Jerusalem. See the crown with which his mother crowned him on his wedding day, the day of his gladness.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 1, 'How beautiful you are, my beloved, how beautiful! Your eyes behind your veil are like doves. Your hair falls in waves, like a flock of goats frisking down the slopes of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 2, 'Your teeth are as white as sheep, newly shorn and washed. They are perfectly matched; not one is missing.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 3, 'Your lips are like a ribbon of scarlet. Oh, how beautiful your mouth! Your cheeks behind your veil are like pomegranate halves--lovely and delicious.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 4, 'Your neck is as stately as the tower of David, jeweled with the shields of a thousand heroes.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 5, 'Your breasts are like twin fawns of a gazelle, feeding among the lilies.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 6, 'Before the dawn comes and the shadows flee away, I will go to the mountain of myrrh and to the hill of frankincense.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 7, 'You are so beautiful, my beloved, so perfect in every part.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 8, '"Come with me from Lebanon, my bride. Come down from the top of Mount Amana, from Mount Senir and Mount Hermon, where lions have their dens and panthers prowl.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 9, 'You have ravished my heart, my treasure, my bride. I am overcome by one glance of your eyes, by a single bead of your necklace.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 10, 'How sweet is your love, my treasure, my bride! How much better it is than wine! Your perfume is more fragrant than the richest of spices.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 11, 'Your lips, my bride, are as sweet as honey. Yes, honey and cream are under your tongue. The scent of your clothing is like that of the mountains and the cedars of Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 12, '"You are like a private garden, my treasure, my bride! You are like a spring that no one else can drink from, a fountain of my own.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 13, 'You are like a lovely orchard bearing precious fruit, with the rarest of perfumes:', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 14, 'nard and saffron, calamus and cinnamon, myrrh and aloes, perfume from every incense tree, and every other lovely spice.', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 15, 'You are a garden fountain, a well of living water, as refreshing as the streams from the Lebanon mountains."', 'NLT'),
(26, 4, 16, 'Awake, north wind! Come, south wind! Blow on my garden and waft its lovely perfume to my lover. Let him come into his garden and eat its choicest fruits.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 1, 'I am here in my garden, my treasure, my bride! I gather my myrrh with my spices and eat my honeycomb with my honey. I drink my wine with my milk. Oh, lover and beloved, eat and drink! Yes, drink deeply of this love!', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 2, 'One night as I was sleeping, my heart awakened in a dream. I heard the voice of my lover. He was knocking at my bedroom door. `Open to me, my darling, my treasure, my lovely dove, he said, `for I have been out in the night. My head is soaked with dew, my hair with the wetness of the night.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 3, '"But I said, `I have taken off my robe. Should I get dressed again? I have washed my feet. Should I get them soiled?''', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 4, '"My lover tried to unlatch the door, and my heart thrilled within me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 5, 'I jumped up to open it. My hands dripped with perfume, my fingers with lovely myrrh, as I pulled back the bolt.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 6, 'I opened to my lover, but he was gone. I yearned for even his voice! I searched for him, but I couldn''t find him anywhere. I called to him, but there was no reply.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 7, 'The watchmen found me as they were making their rounds; they struck and wounded me. The watchman on the wall tore off my veil.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 8, '"Make this promise to me, O women of Jerusalem! If you find my beloved one, tell him that I am sick with love."', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 9, 'O woman of rare beauty, what is it about your loved one that brings you to tell us this?', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 10, 'My lover is dark and dazzling, better than ten thousand others!', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 11, 'His head is the finest gold, and his hair is wavy and black.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 12, 'His eyes are like doves beside brooks of water; they are set like jewels.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 13, 'His cheeks are like sweetly scented beds of spices. His lips are like perfumed lilies. His breath is like myrrh.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 14, 'His arms are like round bars of gold, set with chrysolite. His body is like bright ivory, aglow with sapphires.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 15, 'His legs are like pillars of marble set in sockets of the finest gold, strong as the cedars of Lebanon. None can rival him.', 'NLT'),
(26, 5, 16, 'His mouth is altogether sweet; he is lovely in every way. Such, O women of Jerusalem, is my lover, my friend.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 1, 'O rarest of beautiful women, where has your lover gone? We will help you find him.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 2, 'He has gone down to his garden, to his spice beds, to graze and to gather the lilies.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 3, 'I am my lovers, and my lover is mine. He grazes among the lilies!', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 4, 'O my beloved, you are as beautiful as the lovely town of Tirzah. Yes, as beautiful as Jerusalem! You are as majestic as an army with banners!', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 5, 'Look away, for your eyes overcome me! Your hair falls in waves, like a flock of goats frisking down the slopes of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 6, 'Your teeth are as white as newly washed sheep. They are perfectly matched; not one is missing.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 7, 'Your cheeks behind your veil are like pomegranate halves--lovely and delicious.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 8, 'There may be sixty wives, all queens, and eighty concubines and unnumbered virgins available to me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 9, 'But I would still choose my dove, my perfect one, the only beloved daughter of her mother! The young women are delighted when they see her; even queens and concubines sing her praises!', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 10, '`Who is this, they ask, `arising like the dawn, as fair as the moon, as bright as the sun, as majestic as an army with banners?', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 11, '"I went down into the grove of nut trees and out to the valley to see the new growth brought on by spring. I wanted to see whether the grapevines were budding yet, or whether the pomegranates were blossoming.', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 12, 'Before I realized it, I found myself in my princely bed with my beloved one. "', 'NLT'),
(26, 6, 13, 'Return, return to us, O maid of Shulam. Come back, come back, that we may see you once again. Why do you gaze so intently at this young woman of Shulam, as she moves so gracefully between two lines of dancers?', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 1, 'How beautiful are your sandaled feet, O queenly maiden. Your rounded thighs are like jewels, the work of a skilled craftsman.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 2, 'Your navel is as delicious as a goblet filled with wine. Your belly is lovely, like a heap of wheat set about with lilies.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 3, 'Your breasts are like twin fawns of a gazelle.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 4, 'Your neck is as stately as an ivory tower. Your eyes are like the sparkling pools in Heshbon by the gate of Bath-rabbim. Your nose is as fine as the tower of Lebanon overlooking Damascus.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 5, 'Your head is as majestic as Mount Carmel, and the sheen of your hair radiates royalty. A king is held captive in your queenly tresses.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 6, '"Oh, how delightful you are, my beloved; how pleasant for utter delight!', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 7, 'You are tall and slim like a palm tree, and your breasts are like its clusters of dates.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 8, 'I said, `I will climb up into the palm tree and take hold of its branches.'' Now may your breasts be like grape clusters, and the scent of your breath like apples.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 9, 'May your kisses be as exciting as the best wine, smooth and sweet, flowing gently over lips and teeth. "', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 10, 'I am my lovers, the one he desires.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 11, 'Come, my love, let us go out into the fields and spend the night among the wildflowers.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 12, 'Let us get up early and go out to the vineyards. Let us see whether the vines have budded, whether the blossoms have opened, and whether the pomegranates are in flower. And there I will give you my love.', 'NLT'),
(26, 7, 13, 'There the mandrakes give forth their fragrance, and the rarest fruits are at our doors, the new as well as old, for I have stored them up for you, my lover.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 1, 'Oh, if only you were my brother, who nursed at my mothers breast. Then I could kiss you no matter who was watching, and no one would criticize me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 2, 'I would bring you to my childhood home, and there you would teach me. I would give you spiced wine to drink, my sweet pomegranate wine.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 3, 'Your left hand would be under my head and your right hand would embrace me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 4, '"I want you to promise, O women of Jerusalem, not to awaken love until the time is right. "', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 5, 'Who is this coming up from the desert, leaning on her lover? I aroused you under the apple tree, where your mother gave you birth, where in great pain she delivered you.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 6, 'Place me like a seal over your heart, or like a seal on your arm. For love is as strong as death, and its jealousy is as enduring as the grave. Love flashes like fire, the brightest kind of flame.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 7, 'Many waters cannot quench love; neither can rivers drown it. If a man tried to buy love with everything he owned, his offer would be utterly despised.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 8, 'We have a little sister too young for breasts. What will we do if someone asks to marry her?', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 9, 'If she is chaste, we will strengthen and encourage her. But if she is promiscuous, we will shut her off from men.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 10, 'I am chaste, and I am now full breasted. And my lover is content with me.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 11, '"Solomon has a vineyard at Baal-hamon, which he rents to some farmers there. Each of them pays one thousand pieces of silver for its use.', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 12, 'But as for my own vineyard, O Solomon, you can take my thousand pieces of silver. And I will give two hundred pieces of silver to those who care for its vines."', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 13, 'O my beloved, lingering in the gardens, how wonderful that your companions can listen to your voice. Let me hear it, too!', 'NLT'),
(26, 8, 14, 'Come quickly, my love! Move like a swift gazelle or a young deer on the mountains of spices.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 1, 'These visions concerning Judah and Jerusalem came to Isaiah son of Amoz during the reigns of Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah--all kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 2, 'Hear, O heavens! Listen, O earth! This is what the LORD says: "The children I raised and cared for have turned against me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 3, 'Even the animals--the donkey and the ox--know their owner and appreciate his care, but not my people Israel. No matter what I do for them, they still do not understand."', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 4, 'Oh, what a sinful nation they are! They are loaded down with a burden of guilt. They are evil and corrupt children who have turned away from the LORD. They have despised the Holy One of Israel, cutting themselves off from his help.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 5, 'Why do you continue to invite punishment? Must you rebel forever? Your head is injured, and your heart is sick.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 6, 'You are sick from head to foot--covered with bruises, welts, and infected wounds--without any ointments or bandages.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 7, 'Your country lies in ruins, and your cities are burned. As you watch, foreigners plunder your fields and destroy everything they see.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 8, 'Jerusalem stands abandoned like a watchman''s shelter in a vineyard or field after the harvest is over. It is as helpless as a city under siege.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 9, 'If the LORD Almighty had not spared a few of us, we would have been wiped out as completely as Sodom and Gomorrah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 10, 'Listen to the LORD, you leaders of Israel! Listen to the law of our God, people of Israel. You act just like the rulers and people of Sodom and Gomorrah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 11, '"I am sick of your sacrifices," says the LORD. "Don''t bring me any more burnt offerings! I don''t want the fat from your rams or other animals. I don''t want to see the blood from your offerings of bulls and rams and goats.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 12, 'Why do you keep parading through my courts with your worthless sacrifices?', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 13, 'The incense you bring me is a stench in my nostrils! Your celebrations of the new moon and the Sabbath day, and your special days for fasting--even your most pious meetings--are all sinful and false. I want nothing more to do with them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 14, 'I hate all your festivals and sacrifices. I cannot stand the sight of them!', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 15, 'From now on, when you lift up your hands in prayer, I will refuse to look. Even though you offer many prayers, I will not listen. For your hands are covered with the blood of your innocent victims.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 16, 'Wash yourselves and be clean! Let me no longer see your evil deeds. Give up your wicked ways.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 17, 'Learn to do good. Seek justice. Help the oppressed. Defend the orphan. Fight for the rights of widows.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 18, '"Come now, let us argue this out," says the LORD. "No matter how deep the stain of your sins, I can remove it. I can make you as clean as freshly fallen snow. Even if you are stained as red as crimson, I can make you as white as wool.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 19, 'If you will only obey me and let me help you, then you will have plenty to eat.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 20, 'But if you keep turning away and refusing to listen, you will be destroyed by your enemies. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 21, 'See how Jerusalem, once so faithful, has become a prostitute. Once the home of justice and righteousness, she is now filled with murderers.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 22, 'Once like pure silver, you have become like worthless slag. Once so pure, you are now like watered-down wine.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 23, 'Your leaders are rebels, the companions of thieves. All of them take bribes and refuse to defend the orphans and the widows.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 24, 'Therefore, the Lord, the LORD Almighty, the Mighty One of Israel, says, "I will pour out my fury on you, my enemies!', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 25, 'I will turn against you. I will melt you down and skim off your slag. I will remove all your impurities.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 26, 'Afterward I will give you good judges and wise counselors like the ones you used to have. Then Jerusalem will again be called the Home of Justice and the Faithful City."', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 27, 'Because the LORD is just and righteous, the repentant people of Jerusalem will be redeemed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 28, 'But all sinners will be completely destroyed, for they refuse to come to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 29, 'Shame will cover you when you think of the times you offered sacrifices to idols in your groves of sacred oaks. You will blush when you think of all the sins you committed in your sacred gardens.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 30, 'You will wither away like an oak or garden without water.', 'NLT'),
(27, 1, 31, 'The strongest among you will disappear like burning straw. Your evil deeds are the spark that will set the straw on fire, and no one will be able to put it out.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 1, 'This is another vision that Isaiah son of Amoz saw concerning Judah and Jerusalem:', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 2, 'In the last days, the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem will become the most important place on earth. People from all over the world will go there to worship.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 3, 'Many nations will come and say, "Come, let us go up to the mountain of the LORD, to the Temple of the God of Israel. There he will teach us his ways, so that we may obey him." For in those days the LORD''s teaching and his word will go out from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 4, 'The LORD will settle international disputes. All the nations will beat their swords into plowshares and their spears into pruning hooks. All wars will stop, and military training will come to an end.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 5, 'Come, people of Israel, let us walk in the light of the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 6, 'The LORD has rejected the people of Israel because they have made alliances with foreigners from the East who practice magic and divination, just like the Philistines.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 7, 'Israel has vast treasures of silver and gold and many horses and chariots.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 8, 'The land is filled with idols. The people bow down and worship these things they have made.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 9, 'So now everyone will be humbled and brought low. The LORD cannot simply ignore their sins!', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 10, 'Crawl into caves in the rocks. Hide from the terror of the LORD and the glory of his majesty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 11, 'The day is coming when your pride will be brought low and the LORD alone will be exalted.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 12, 'In that day the LORD Almighty will punish the proud, bringing them down to the dust.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 13, 'He will cut down the tall cedars of Lebanon and the mighty oaks of Bashan.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 14, 'He will level the high mountains and hills.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 15, 'He will break down every high tower and wall.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 16, 'He will destroy the great trading ships and all the small boats in the harbor.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 17, 'The arrogance of all people will be brought low. Their pride will lie in the dust. The LORD alone will be exalted!', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 18, 'Idols will be utterly abolished and destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 19, 'When the LORD rises to shake the earth, his enemies will crawl with fear into holes in the ground. They will hide in caves in the rocks from the terror of the LORD and the glory of his majesty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 20, 'They will abandon their gold and silver idols to the moles and bats.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 21, 'They will crawl into caverns and hide among the jagged rocks at the tops of cliffs. In this way, they will try to escape the terror of the LORD and the glory of his majesty as he rises to shake the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 2, 22, 'Stop putting your trust in mere humans. They are as frail as breath. How can they be of help to anyone?', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 1, 'The Lord, the LORD Almighty, will cut off the supplies of food and water from Jerusalem and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 2, 'He will destroy all the nation''s leaders--the heroes, soldiers, judges, prophets, diviners, elders,', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 3, 'army officers, honorable citizens, advisers, skilled magicians, and expert enchanters.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 4, 'Then he will appoint children to rule over them, and anarchy will prevail.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 5, 'People will take advantage of each other--man against man, neighbor fighting neighbor. Young people will revolt against authority, and nobodies will sneer at honorable people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 6, 'In those days a man will say to his brother, "Since you have a cloak, you be our leader! Take charge of this heap of ruins!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 7, '"No!" he will reply. "I can''t help. I don''t have any extra food or clothes. Don''t ask me to get involved!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 8, 'Judah and Jerusalem will lie in ruins because they speak out against the LORD and refuse to obey him. They have offended his glorious presence among them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 9, 'The very look on their faces gives them away and displays their guilt. They sin openly like the people of Sodom. They are not one bit ashamed. How terrible it will be for them! They have brought about their own destruction.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 10, 'But all will be well for those who are godly. Tell them, "You will receive a wonderful reward!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 11, 'But say to the wicked, "Your destruction is sure. You, too, will get what you deserve. Your well-earned punishment is on the way."', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 12, 'Children oppress my people, and women rule over them. O my people, can''t you see what fools your rulers are? They are leading you down a pretty garden path to destruction.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 13, 'The LORD takes his place in court. He is the great prosecuting attorney, presenting his case against his people!', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 14, 'The leaders and the princes will be the first to feel the LORD''s judgment. "You have ruined Israel, which is my vineyard. You have taken advantage of the poor, filling your barns with grain extorted from helpless people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 15, 'How dare you grind my people into the dust like that!" demands the Lord, the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 16, 'Next the LORD will judge the women of Jerusalem, who walk around with their noses in the air, with tinkling ornaments on their ankles. Their eyes rove among the crowds, flirting with the men.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 17, 'The Lord will send a plague of scabs to ornament their heads. Yes, the LORD will make them bald for all to see!', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 18, 'The Lord will strip away their artful beauty--their ornaments, headbands, and crescent necklaces;', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 19, 'their earrings, bracelets, and veils of shimmering gauze.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 20, 'Gone will be their scarves, ankle chains, sashes, perfumes, and charms;', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 21, 'their rings, jewels,', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 22, 'party clothes, gowns, capes, and purses;', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 23, 'their mirrors, linen garments, head ornaments, and shawls.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 24, 'Instead of smelling of sweet perfume, they will stink. They will wear ropes for sashes, and their well-set hair will fall out. They will wear rough sackcloth instead of rich robes. Their beauty will be gone. Only shame will be left to them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 25, 'The men of the city will die in battle.', 'NLT'),
(27, 3, 26, 'The gates of Jerusalem will weep and mourn. The city will be like a ravaged woman, huddled on the ground.', 'NLT'),
(27, 4, 1, 'In that day few men will be left alive. Seven women will fight over each of them and say, "Let us all marry you! We will provide our own food and clothing. Only let us be called by your name so we won''t be mocked as old maids."', 'NLT'),
(27, 4, 2, 'But in the future, Israel--the branch of the LORD--will be lush and beautiful, and the fruit of the land will be the pride of its people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 4, 3, 'All those whose names are written down, who have survived the destruction of Jerusalem, will be a holy people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 4, 4, 'The Lord will wash the moral filth from the women of Jerusalem. He will cleanse Jerusalem of its bloodstains by a spirit of judgment that burns like fire.', 'NLT'),
(27, 4, 5, 'Then the LORD will provide shade for Jerusalem and all who assemble there. There will be a canopy of smoke and cloud throughout the day and clouds of fire at night, covering the glorious land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 4, 6, 'It will be a shelter from daytime heat and a hiding place from storms and rain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 1, 'Now I will sing a song for the one I love about his vineyard: My beloved has a vineyard on a rich and fertile hill.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 2, 'He plowed the land, cleared its stones, and planted it with choice vines. In the middle he built a watchtower and carved a winepress in the nearby rocks. Then he waited for a harvest of sweet grapes, but the grapes that grew were wild and sour.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 3, '"Now, you people of Jerusalem and Judah, you have heard the case; you be the judges.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 4, 'What more could I have done to cultivate a rich harvest? Why did my vineyard give me wild grapes when I expected sweet ones?', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 5, 'Now this is what I am going to do to my vineyard: I will tear down its fences and let it be destroyed. I will break down its walls and let the animals trample it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 6, 'I will make it a wild place. I will not prune the vines or hoe the ground. I will let it be overgrown with briers and thorns. I will command the clouds to drop no more rain on it."', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 7, 'This is the story of the LORD''s people. They are the vineyard of the LORD Almighty. Israel and Judah are his pleasant garden. He expected them to yield a crop of justice, but instead he found bloodshed. He expected to find righteousness, but instead he heard cries of oppression.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 8, 'Destruction is certain for you who buy up property so others have no place to live. Your homes are built on great estates so you can be alone in the land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 9, 'But the LORD Almighty has sealed your awful fate. With my own ears I heard him say, "Many beautiful homes will stand deserted, the owners dead or gone.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 10, 'Ten acres of vineyard will not produce even six gallons of wine. Ten measures of seed will yield only one measure of grain."', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 11, 'Destruction is certain for you who get up early to begin long drinking bouts that last late into the night.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 12, 'You furnish lovely music and wine at your grand parties; the harps, lyres, tambourines, and flutes are superb! But you never think about the LORD or notice what he is doing.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 13, 'So I will send my people into exile far away because they do not know me. The great and honored among them will starve, and the common people will die of thirst.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 14, 'The grave is licking its chops in anticipation of Jerusalem, this delicious morsel. Her great and lowly will be swallowed up, with all her drunken crowds.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 15, 'In that day the arrogant will be brought down to the dust; the proud will be humbled.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 16, 'But the LORD Almighty is exalted by his justice. The holiness of God is displayed by his righteousness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 17, 'In those days flocks will feed among the ruins; lambs and kids will pasture there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 18, 'Destruction is certain for those who drag their sins behind them, tied with cords of falsehood.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 19, 'They even mock the Holy One of Israel and say, "Hurry up and do something! Quick, show us what you can do. We want to see what you have planned."', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 20, 'Destruction is certain for those who say that evil is good and good is evil; that dark is light and light is dark; that bitter is sweet and sweet is bitter.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 21, 'Destruction is certain for those who think they are wise and consider themselves to be clever.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 22, 'Destruction is certain for those who are heroes when it comes to drinking, who boast about all the liquor they can hold.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 23, 'They take bribes to pervert justice. They let the wicked go free while punishing the innocent.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 24, 'Therefore, they will all disappear like burning straw. Their roots will rot and their flowers wither, for they have rejected the law of the LORD Almighty. They have despised the word of the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 25, 'That is why the anger of the LORD burns against his people. That is why he has raised his fist to crush them. The hills tremble, and the rotting bodies of his people are thrown as garbage into the streets. But even then the LORD''s anger will not be satisfied. His fist is still poised to strike!', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 26, 'He will send a signal to the nations far away. He will whistle to those at the ends of the earth, and they will come racing toward Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 27, 'They will not get tired or stumble. They will run without stopping for rest or sleep. Not a belt will be loose, not a sandal thong broken.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 28, 'Their arrows will be sharp and their bows ready for battle. Sparks will fly from their horses'' hooves as the wheels of their chariots spin like the wind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 29, 'Roaring like lions, they will pounce on their prey. They will seize my people and carry them off into captivity, and no one will be there to rescue them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 5, 30, 'The enemy nations will growl over their victims like the roaring of the sea. A cloud of darkness and sorrow will hover over Israel. The clouds will blot out the light.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 1, 'In the year King Uzziah died, I saw the Lord. He was sitting on a lofty throne, and the train of his robe filled the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 2, 'Hovering around him were mighty seraphim, each with six wings. With two wings they covered their faces, with two they covered their feet, and with the remaining two they flew.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 3, 'In a great chorus they sang, "Holy, holy, holy is the LORD Almighty! The whole earth is filled with his glory!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 4, 'The glorious singing shook the Temple to its foundations, and the entire sanctuary was filled with smoke.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 5, 'Then I said, "My destruction is sealed, for I am a sinful man and a member of a sinful race. Yet I have seen the King, the LORD Almighty!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 6, 'Then one of the seraphim flew over to the altar, and he picked up a burning coal with a pair of tongs.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 7, 'He touched my lips with it and said, "See, this coal has touched your lips. Now your guilt is removed, and your sins are forgiven."', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 8, 'Then I heard the Lord asking, "Whom should I send as a messenger to my people? Who will go for us?" And I said, "Lord, I''ll go! Send me."', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 9, 'And he said, "Yes, go. But tell my people this: `You will hear my words, but you will not understand. You will see what I do, but you will not perceive its meaning.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 10, 'Harden the hearts of these people. Close their ears, and shut their eyes. That way, they will not see with their eyes, hear with their ears, understand with their hearts, and turn to me for healing."', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 11, 'Then I said, "Lord, how long must I do this?" And he replied, "Until their cities are destroyed, with no one left in them. Until their houses are deserted and the whole country is an utter wasteland.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 12, 'Do not stop until the LORD has sent everyone away to distant lands and the entire land of Israel lies deserted.', 'NLT'),
(27, 6, 13, 'Even if only a tenth--a remnant--survive, it will be invaded again and burned. Israel will remain a stump, like a tree that is cut down, but the stump will be a holy seed that will grow again."', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 1, 'During the reign of Ahaz son of Jotham and grandson of Uzziah, Jerusalem was attacked by King Rezin of Aram and King Pekah of Israel, the son of Remaliah. The city withstood the attack, however, and was not taken.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 2, 'The news had come to the royal court: "Aram is allied with Israel against us!" So the hearts of the king and his people trembled with fear, just as trees shake in a storm.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 3, 'Then the LORD said to Isaiah, "Go out to meet King Ahaz, you and your son Shear-jashub. You will find the king at the end of the aqueduct that feeds water into the upper pool, near the road leading to the field where cloth is bleached.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 4, 'Tell him to stop worrying. Tell him he doesn''t need to fear the fierce anger of those two burned-out embers, King Rezin of Aram and Pekah son of Remaliah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 5, '"Yes, the kings of Aram and Israel are coming against you. They are saying,', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 6, '`We will invade Judah and throw its people into panic. Then we will fight our way into Jerusalem and install the son of Tabeel as Judah''s king.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 7, '"But this is what the Sovereign LORD says: This invasion will never happen,', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 8, 'because Aram is no stronger than its capital, Damascus. And Damascus is no stronger than its king, Rezin. As for Israel, within sixty-five years it will be crushed and completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 9, 'Israel is no stronger than its capital, Samaria. And Samaria is no stronger than its king, Pekah son of Remaliah. You do not believe me? If you want me to protect you, learn to believe what I say."', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 10, 'Not long after this, the LORD sent this message to King Ahaz:', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 11, '"Ask me for a sign, Ahaz, to prove that I will crush your enemies as I have promised. Ask for anything you like, and make it as difficult as you want."', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 12, 'But the king refused. "No," he said, "I wouldn''t test the LORD like that."', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 13, 'Then Isaiah said, "Listen well, you royal family of David! You aren''t satisfied to exhaust my patience. You exhaust the patience of God as well!', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 14, 'All right then, the Lord himself will choose the sign. Look! The virgin will conceive a child! She will give birth to a son and will call him Immanuel--`God is with us.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 15, 'By the time this child is old enough to eat curds and honey, he will know enough to choose what is right and reject what is wrong.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 16, 'But before he knows right from wrong, the two kings you fear so much--the kings of Israel and Aram--will both be dead.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 17, '"The LORD will bring a terrible curse on you, your nation, and your family. You will soon experience greater terror than has been known in all the years since Solomon''s empire was divided into Israel and Judah. The mighty king of Assyria will come with his great army!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 18, 'In that day the LORD will whistle for the army of Upper Egypt and for the army of Assyria. They will swarm around you like flies. Like bees, they will sting and kill.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 19, 'They will come in vast hordes, spreading across the whole land. They will settle in the fertile areas and also in the desolate valleys, caves, and thorny places.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 20, 'In that day the Lord will take this "razor"--these Assyrians you have hired to protect you--and use it to shave off everything: your land, your crops, and your people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 21, 'When they finally stop plundering, a farmer will be fortunate to have a cow and two sheep left.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 22, 'The few people still left in the land will live on curds and wild honey because that is all the land will produce.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 23, 'In that day the lush vineyards, now worth as much as a thousand pieces of silver, will become patches of briers and thorns.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 24, 'The entire land will be one vast brier patch, a hunting ground overrun by wildlife.', 'NLT'),
(27, 7, 25, 'No one will go to the fertile hillsides where the gardens once grew, for briers and thorns will cover them. Cattle, sheep, and goats will graze there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 1, 'Again the LORD said to me, "Make a large signboard and clearly write this name on it: Maher-shalal-hash-baz. "', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 2, 'I asked Uriah the priest and Zechariah son of Jeberekiah, both known as honest men, to testify that I had written it before the child was conceived.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 3, 'Then I slept with my wife, and she became pregnant and had a son. And the LORD said, "Call him Maher-shalal-hash-baz.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 4, 'This name prophesies that within a couple of years, before this child is old enough to say `Papa'' or `Mama,'' the king of Assyria will invade both Damascus and Samaria and carry away their riches."', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 5, 'Then the LORD spoke to me again and said,', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 6, '"The people of Judah have rejected my gentle care and are rejoicing over what will happen to King Rezin and King Pekah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 7, 'Therefore, the Lord will overwhelm them with a mighty flood from the Euphrates River--the king of Assyria and all his mighty armies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 8, 'This flood will overflow all its channels and sweep into Judah. It will submerge Immanuel''s land from one end to the other.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 9, '"The Assyrians will cry, `Do your best to defend yourselves, but you will be shattered! Listen all you nations. Prepare for battle--and die! Yes, die!', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 10, 'Call your councils of war, develop your strategies, prepare your plans of attack--and then die! For God is with us! ''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 11, 'The LORD has said to me in the strongest terms: "Do not think like everyone else does.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 12, 'Do not be afraid that some plan conceived behind closed doors will be the end of you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 13, 'Do not fear anything except the LORD Almighty. He alone is the Holy One. If you fear him, you need fear nothing else.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 14, 'He will keep you safe. But to Israel and Judah he will be a stone that causes people to stumble and a rock that makes them fall. And for the people of Jerusalem he will be a trap that entangles them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 15, 'Many of them will stumble and fall, never to rise again. Many will be captured."', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 16, 'I will write down all these things as a testimony of what the LORD will do. I will entrust it to my disciples, who will pass it down to future generations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 17, 'I will wait for the LORD to help us, though he has turned away from the people of Israel. My only hope is in him.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 18, 'I and the children the LORD has given me have names that reveal the plans the LORD Almighty has for his people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 19, 'So why are you trying to find out the future by consulting mediums and psychics? Do not listen to their whisperings and mutterings. Can the living find out the future from the dead? Why not ask your God?', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 20, '"Check their predictions against my testimony," says the LORD. "If their predictions are different from mine, it is because there is no light or truth in them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 21, 'My people will be led away as captives, weary and hungry. And because they are hungry, they will rage and shake their fists at heaven and curse their king and their God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 8, 22, 'Wherever they look, there will be trouble and anguish and dark despair. They will be thrown out into the darkness."', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 1, 'Nevertheless, that time of darkness and despair will not go on forever. The land of Zebulun and Naphtali will soon be humbled, but there will be a time in the future when Galilee of the Gentiles, which lies along the road that runs between the Jordan and the sea, will be filled with glory.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 2, 'The people who walk in darkness will see a great light--a light that will shine on all who live in the land where death casts its shadow.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 3, 'Israel will again be great, and its people will rejoice as people rejoice at harvesttime. They will shout with joy like warriors dividing the plunder.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 4, 'For God will break the chains that bind his people and the whip that scourges them, just as he did when he destroyed the army of Midian with Gideon''s little band.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 5, 'In that day of peace, battle gear will no longer be issued. Never again will uniforms be bloodstained by war. All such equipment will be burned.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 6, 'For a child is born to us, a son is given to us. And the government will rest on his shoulders. These will be his royal titles: Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 7, 'His ever expanding, peaceful government will never end. He will rule forever with fairness and justice from the throne of his ancestor David. The passionate commitment of the LORD Almighty will guarantee this!', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 8, 'The Lord has spoken out against that braggart Israel,', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 9, 'and the people of Israel and Samaria will soon discover it. In their pride and arrogance they say,', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 10, '"Our land lies in ruins now, but we will rebuild it better than before. We will replace the broken bricks with cut stone, the fallen sycamore trees with cedars."', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 11, 'The LORD will reply to their bragging by bringing Rezin''s enemies, the Assyrians, against them--', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 12, 'along with Arameans from the east and Philistines from the west. With bared fangs, they will devour Israel. But even then the LORD''s anger will not be satisfied. His fist is still poised to strike.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 13, 'For after all this punishment, the people will still not repent and turn to the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 14, 'Therefore, in a single day, the LORD will destroy both the head and the tail, the palm branch and the reed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 15, 'The leaders of Israel are the head, and the lying prophets are the tail.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 16, 'For the leaders of the people have led them down the path of destruction.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 17, 'That is why the Lord has no joy in the young men and no mercy on even the widows and orphans. For they are all hypocrites, speaking wickedness with lies. But even then the LORD''s anger will not be satisfied. His fist is still poised to strike.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 18, 'This wickedness is like a brushfire. It burns not only briers and thorns but the forests, too. Its burning sends up vast clouds of smoke.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 19, 'The land is blackened by the fury of the LORD Almighty. The people are fuel for the fire, and no one spares anyone else.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 20, 'They fight against their own neighbors to steal food, but they will still be hungry. In the end they will even eat their own children.', 'NLT'),
(27, 9, 21, 'Manasseh will feed on Ephraim, Ephraim will feed on Manasseh, and both will devour Judah. But even then the LORD''s anger will not be satisfied. His fist is still poised to strike.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 1, 'Destruction is certain for the unjust judges, for those who issue unfair laws.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 2, 'They deprive the poor, the widows, and the orphans of justice. Yes, they rob widows and fatherless children!', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 3, 'What will you do when I send desolation upon you from a distant land? To whom will you turn for help? Where will your treasures be safe?', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 4, 'I will not help you. You will stumble along as prisoners or lie among the dead. But even then the LORD''s anger will not be satisfied. His fist is still poised to strike.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 5, '"Destruction is certain for Assyria, the whip of my anger. Its military power is a club in my hand.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 6, 'Assyria will enslave my people, who are a godless nation. It will plunder them, trampling them like dirt beneath its feet.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 7, 'But the king of Assyria will not know that it is I who sent him. He will merely think he is attacking my people as part of his plan to conquer the world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 8, 'He will say, `Each of my princes will soon be a king, ruling a conquered land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 9, 'We will destroy Calno just as we did Carchemish. Hamath will fall before us as Arpad did. And we will destroy Samaria just as we did Damascus.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 10, 'Yes, we have finished off many a kingdom whose gods were far greater than those in Jerusalem and Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 11, 'So when we have defeated Samaria and her gods, we will destroy Jerusalem with hers.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 12, 'After the Lord has used the king of Assyria to accomplish his purposes in Jerusalem, he will turn against the king of Assyria and punish him--for he is proud and arrogant.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 13, 'He boasts, "By my own power and wisdom I have won these wars. By my own strength I have captured many lands, destroyed their kings, and carried off their treasures.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 14, 'By my greatness I have robbed their nests of riches and gathered up kingdoms as a farmer gathers eggs. No one can even flap a wing against me or utter a peep of protest."', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 15, 'Can the ax boast greater power than the person who uses it? Is the saw greater than the person who saws? Can a whip strike unless a hand is moving it? Can a cane walk by itself?', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 16, 'Listen now, king of Assyria! Because of all your evil boasting, the Lord, the LORD Almighty, will send a plague among your proud troops, and a flaming fire will ignite your glory.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 17, 'The LORD, the Light of Israel and the Holy One, will be a flaming fire that will destroy them. In a single night he will burn those thorns and briers, the Assyrians.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 18, 'Assyria''s vast army is like a glorious forest, yet it will be destroyed. The LORD will completely destroy Assyria''s warriors, and they will waste away like sick people in a plague.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 19, 'Only a few from all that mighty army will survive--so few that a child could count them!', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 20, 'Then at last those left in Israel and Judah will trust the LORD, the Holy One of Israel. They will no longer depend on the Assyrians, who would destroy them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 21, 'A remnant of them will return to the Mighty God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 22, 'But though the people of Israel are as numerous as the sand on the seashore, only a few of them will return at that time. The LORD has rightly decided to destroy his people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 23, 'Yes, the Lord, the LORD Almighty, has already decided to consume them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 24, 'So this is what the Lord, the LORD Almighty, says: "My people in Jerusalem, do not be afraid of the Assyrians when they oppress you just as the Egyptians did long ago.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 25, 'It will not last very long. In a little while my anger against you will end, and then my anger will rise up to destroy them."', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 26, 'The LORD Almighty will beat them with his whip, as he did when Gideon triumphed over the Midianites at the rock of Oreb, or when the LORD''s staff was raised to drown the Egyptian army in the sea.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 27, 'In that day the LORD will end the bondage of his people. He will break the yoke of slavery and lift it from their shoulders.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 28, 'Look, the mighty armies of Assyria are coming! They are now at Aiath, now at Migron. They are storing some of their equipment at Micmash.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 29, 'They are crossing the pass and are staying overnight at Geba. Fear strikes the city of Ramah. All the people of Gibeah--the city of Saul--are running for their lives.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 30, 'Well may you scream in terror, you people of Gallim! Shout out a warning to Laishah, for the mighty army comes. Poor Anathoth, what a fate is yours!', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 31, 'There go the people of Madmenah, all fleeing. And the citizens of Gebim are preparing to run.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 32, 'But the enemy stops at Nob for the rest of that day. He shakes his fist at Mount Zion in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 33, 'But look! The Lord, the LORD Almighty, will chop down the mighty tree! He will destroy all that vast army of Assyria--officers and high officials alike.', 'NLT'),
(27, 10, 34, 'The Mighty One will cut down the enemy as an ax cuts down the forest trees in Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 1, 'Out of the stump of David''s family will grow a shoot--yes, a new Branch bearing fruit from the old root.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 2, 'And the Spirit of the LORD will rest on him--the Spirit of wisdom and understanding, the Spirit of counsel and might, the Spirit of knowledge and the fear of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 3, 'He will delight in obeying the LORD. He will never judge by appearance, false evidence, or hearsay.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 4, 'He will defend the poor and the exploited. He will rule against the wicked and destroy them with the breath of his mouth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 5, 'He will be clothed with fairness and truth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 6, 'In that day the wolf and the lamb will live together; the leopard and the goat will be at peace. Calves and yearlings will be safe among lions, and a little child will lead them all.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 7, 'The cattle will graze among bears. Cubs and calves will lie down together. And lions will eat grass as the livestock do.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 8, 'Babies will crawl safely among poisonous snakes. Yes, a little child will put its hand in a nest of deadly snakes and pull it out unharmed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 9, 'Nothing will hurt or destroy in all my holy mountain. And as the waters fill the sea, so the earth will be filled with people who know the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 10, 'In that day the heir to David''s throne will be a banner of salvation to all the world. The nations will rally to him, for the land where he lives will be a glorious place.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 11, 'In that day the Lord will bring back a remnant of his people for the second time, returning them to the land of Israel from Assyria, Lower Egypt, Upper Egypt, Ethiopia, Elam, Babylonia, Hamath, and all the distant coastlands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 12, 'He will raise a flag among the nations for Israel to rally around. He will gather the scattered people of Judah from the ends of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 13, 'Then at last the jealousy between Israel and Judah will end. They will not fight against each other anymore.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 14, 'They will join forces to swoop down on Philistia to the west. Together they will attack and plunder the nations to the east. They will occupy all the lands of Edom, Moab, and Ammon.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 15, 'The LORD will make a dry path through the Red Sea. He will wave his hand over the Euphrates River, sending a mighty wind to divide it into seven streams that can easily be crossed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 11, 16, 'He will make a highway from Assyria for the remnant there, just as he did for Israel long ago when they returned from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(27, 12, 1, 'In that day you will sing: "Praise the LORD! He was angry with me, but now he comforts me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 12, 2, 'See, God has come to save me. I will trust in him and not be afraid. The LORD GOD is my strength and my song; he has become my salvation."', 'NLT'),
(27, 12, 3, 'With joy you will drink deeply from the fountain of salvation!', 'NLT'),
(27, 12, 4, 'In that wonderful day you will sing: "Thank the LORD! Praise his name! Tell the world what he has done. Oh, how mighty he is!', 'NLT'),
(27, 12, 5, 'Sing to the LORD, for he has done wonderful things. Make known his praise around the world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 12, 6, 'Let all the people of Jerusalem shout his praise with joy! For great is the Holy One of Israel who lives among you."', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 1, 'Isaiah son of Amoz received this message concerning the destruction of Babylon:', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 2, '"See the flags waving as the enemy attacks. Cheer them on, O Israel! Wave to them as they march against Babylon to destroy the palaces of the high and mighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 3, 'I, the LORD, have assigned this task to these armies, and they will rejoice when I am exalted. I have called them to satisfy my anger."', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 4, 'Hear the noise on the mountains! Listen, as the armies march! It is the noise and the shout of many nations. The LORD Almighty has brought them here to form an army.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 5, 'They came from countries far away. They are the LORD''s weapons; they carry his anger with them and will destroy the whole land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 6, 'Scream in terror, for the LORD''s time has arrived--the time for the Almighty to destroy.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 7, 'Every arm is paralyzed with fear. Even the strongest hearts melt', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 8, 'and are afraid. Fear grips them with terrible pangs, like those of a woman about to give birth. They look helplessly at one another as the flames of the burning city reflect on their faces.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 9, 'For see, the day of the LORD is coming--the terrible day of his fury and fierce anger. The land will be destroyed and all the sinners with it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 10, 'The heavens will be black above them. No light will shine from stars or sun or moon.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 11, '"I, the LORD, will punish the world for its evil and the wicked for their sin. I will crush the arrogance of the proud and the haughtiness of the mighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 12, 'Few will be left alive when I have finished my work. People will be as scarce as gold--more rare than the gold of Ophir.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 13, 'For I will shake the heavens, and the earth will move from its place. I, the LORD Almighty, will show my fury and fierce anger."', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 14, 'Everyone will run until exhausted, rushing back to their own lands like hunted deer, wandering like sheep without a shepherd.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 15, 'Anyone who is captured will be run through with a sword.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 16, 'Their little children will be dashed to death right before their eyes. Their homes will be sacked and their wives raped by the attacking hordes.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 17, 'For I will stir up the Medes against Babylon, and no amount of silver or gold will buy them off.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 18, 'The attacking armies will shoot down the young people with arrows. They will have no mercy on helpless babies and will show no compassion for the children.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 19, 'Babylon, the most glorious of kingdoms, the flower of Chaldean culture, will be devastated like Sodom and Gomorrah when God destroyed them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 20, 'Babylon will never rise again. Generation after generation will come and go, but the land will never again be lived in. Nomads will refuse to camp there, and shepherds will not allow their sheep to stay overnight.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 21, 'Wild animals of the desert will move into the ruined city. The houses will be haunted by howling creatures. Ostriches will live among the ruins, and wild goats will come there to dance.', 'NLT'),
(27, 13, 22, 'Hyenas will howl in its fortresses, and jackals will make their dens in its palaces. Babylon''s days are numbered; its time of destruction will soon arrive.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 1, 'But the LORD will have mercy on the descendants of Jacob. Israel will be his special people once again. He will bring them back to settle once again in their own land. And people from many different nations will come and join them there and become a part of the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 2, 'The nations of the world will help the LORD''s people to return, and those who come to live in their land will serve them. Those who captured Israel will be captured, and Israel will rule over its enemies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 3, 'In that wonderful day when the LORD gives his people rest from sorrow and fear, from slavery and chains,', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 4, 'you will taunt the king of Babylon. You will say, "The mighty man has been destroyed. Yes, your insolence is ended.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 5, 'For the LORD has crushed your wicked power and broken your evil rule.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 6, 'You persecuted the people with unceasing blows of rage and held the nations in your angry grip. Your tyranny was unrestrained.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 7, 'But at last the land is at rest and is quiet. Finally it can sing again!', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 8, 'Even the trees of the forest--the cypress trees and the cedars of Lebanon--sing out this joyous song: `Your power is broken! No one will come to cut us down now!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 9, '"In the place of the dead there is excitement over your arrival. World leaders and mighty kings long dead are there to see you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 10, 'With one voice they all cry out, `Now you are as weak as we are!', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 11, 'Your might and power are gone; they were buried with you. All the pleasant music in your palace has ceased. Now maggots are your sheet and worms your blanket.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 12, '"How you are fallen from heaven, O shining star, son of the morning! You have been thrown down to the earth, you who destroyed the nations of the world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 13, 'For you said to yourself, `I will ascend to heaven and set my throne above God''s stars. I will preside on the mountain of the gods far away in the north.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 14, 'I will climb to the highest heavens and be like the Most High.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 15, 'But instead, you will be brought down to the place of the dead, down to its lowest depths.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 16, 'Everyone there will stare at you and ask, `Can this be the one who shook the earth and the kingdoms of the world?', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 17, 'Is this the one who destroyed the world and made it into a wilderness? Is this the king who demolished the world''s greatest cities and had no mercy on his prisoners?''', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 18, '"The kings of the nations lie in stately glory in their tombs,', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 19, 'but you will be thrown out of your grave like a worthless branch. Like a corpse trampled underfoot, you will be dumped into a mass grave with those killed in battle. You will descend to the pit.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 20, 'You will not be given a proper burial, for you have destroyed your nation and slaughtered your people. Your son will not succeed you as king.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 21, 'Kill the children of this sinner! Do not let them rise and conquer the land or rebuild the cities of the world."', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 22, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "I, myself, have risen against him! I will destroy his children and his children''s children, so they will never sit on his throne.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 23, 'I will make Babylon into a desolate land, a place of porcupines, filled with swamps and marshes. I will sweep the land with the broom of destruction. I, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 24, 'The LORD Almighty has sworn this oath: "It will all happen as I have planned. It will come about according to my purposes.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 25, 'I will break the Assyrians when they are in Israel; I will trample them on my mountains. My people will no longer be their slaves.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 26, 'I have a plan for the whole earth, for my mighty power reaches throughout the world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 27, 'The LORD Almighty has spoken--who can change his plans? When his hand moves, who can stop him?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 28, 'This message came to me the year King Ahaz died:', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 29, 'Do not rejoice, you Philistines, that the king who attacked you is dead. For even though that whip is broken, his son will be worse than his father ever was. From that snake a poisonous snake will be born, a fiery serpent to destroy you!', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 30, 'I will feed the poor in my pasture; the needy will lie down in peace. But as for you, I will wipe you out with famine. I will destroy the few who remain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 31, 'Weep, you Philistine cities, for you are doomed! Melt in fear, for everyone will be destroyed. A powerful army is coming out of the north. Each soldier rushes forward ready to fight.', 'NLT'),
(27, 14, 32, 'What should we tell the enemy messengers? Tell them that the LORD has built Jerusalem, and that the poor of his people will find refuge in its walls.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 1, 'This message came to me concerning Moab: In one night your cities of Ar and Kir will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 2, 'Your people in Dibon will mourn at their temples and shrines, weeping for the fate of Nebo and Medeba. They will shave their heads in sorrow and cut off their beards.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 3, 'They will wear sackcloth as they wander the streets. From every home will come the sound of weeping.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 4, 'The cries from the cities of Heshbon and Elealeh will be heard far away, even in Jahaz! The bravest warriors of Moab will cry out in utter terror.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 5, 'My heart weeps for Moab. Its people flee to Zoar and Eglath-shelishiyah. Weeping, they climb the road to Luhith. Their crying can be heard all along the road to Horonaim.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 6, 'Even the waters of Nimrim are dried up! The grassy banks are scorched, and the tender plants are gone.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 7, 'The desperate refugees take only the possessions they can carry and flee across the Ravine of Willows.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 8, 'The whole land of Moab is a land of weeping from one end to the other--from Eglaim to Beer-elim.', 'NLT'),
(27, 15, 9, 'The stream near Dibon runs red with blood, but I am still not finished with Dibon! Lions will hunt down the survivors, both those who try to run and those who remain behind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 1, 'Moab''s refugees at Sela send lambs to Jerusalem as a token of alliance with the king of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 2, 'The women of Moab are left like homeless birds at the shallow crossings of the Arnon River.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 3, '"Help us," they cry. "Defend us against our enemies. Protect us from their relentless attack. Do not betray us.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 4, 'Let our outcasts stay among you. Hide them from our enemies until the terror is past." When oppression and destruction have ceased and enemy raiders have disappeared,', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 5, 'then David''s throne will be established by love. From that throne a faithful king will reign, one who always does what is just and right.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 6, 'Is this Moab, the proud land we have heard so much about? Its pride and insolence are all gone now!', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 7, 'The entire land of Moab weeps. Yes, you people of Moab, mourn for the delicacies of Kir-hareseth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 8, 'Weep for the abandoned farms of Heshbon and the vineyards at Sibmah. The wine from those vineyards used to make the rulers of the nations drunk. Moab was once like a spreading grapevine. Her tendrils spread out as far as Jazer and trailed out into the desert. Her shoots once reached as far as the Dead Sea.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 9, 'But now the enemy has completely destroyed that vine. So I wail and lament for Jazer and the vineyards of Sibmah. My tears will flow for Heshbon and Elealeh, for their summer fruits and harvests have all been destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 10, 'Gone now is the gladness; gone is the joy of harvest. The happy singing in the vineyards will be heard no more. The treading out of grapes in the winepresses has ceased forever. I have ended all their harvest joys.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 11, 'I will weep for Moab. My sorrow for Kir-hareseth will be very great.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 12, 'On the hilltops the people of Moab will pray in anguish to their idols, but it will do them no good. They will cry to the gods in their temples, but no one will come to save them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 13, 'The LORD has already said this about Moab in the past.', 'NLT'),
(27, 16, 14, 'But now the LORD says, "Within three years, without fail, the glory of Moab will be ended, and few of its people will be left alive."', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 1, 'This message came to me concerning Damascus: "Look, Damascus will disappear! It will become a heap of ruins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 2, 'The cities of Aroer will be deserted. Sheep will graze in the streets and lie down unafraid. There will be no one to chase them away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 3, 'The fortified cities of Israel will also be destroyed, and the power of Damascus will end. The few left in Aram will share the fate of Israel''s departed glory," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 4, '"In that day the glory of Israel will be very dim, for poverty will stalk the land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 5, 'Israel will be abandoned like the grainfields in the valley of Rephaim after the harvest.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 6, 'Only a few of its people will be left, like the stray olives left on the tree after the harvest. Only two or three remain in the highest branches, four or five out on the tips of the limbs. Yes, Israel will be stripped bare of people," says the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 7, 'Then at last the people will think of their Creator and have respect for the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 8, 'They will no longer ask their idols for help or worship what their own hands have made. They will never again bow down to their Asherah poles or burn incense on the altars they built.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 9, 'Their largest cities will be as deserted as overgrown thickets. They will become like the cities the Amorites abandoned when the Israelites came here so long ago.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 10, 'Why? Because you have turned from the God who can save you--the Rock who can hide you. You may plant the finest imported grapevines,', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 11, 'and they may grow so well that they blossom on the very morning you plant them, but you will never pick any grapes from them. Your only harvest will be a load of grief and incurable pain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 12, 'Look! The armies rush forward like waves thundering toward the shore.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 13, 'But though they roar like breakers on a beach, God will silence them. They will flee like chaff scattered by the wind or like dust whirling before a storm.', 'NLT'),
(27, 17, 14, 'In the evening Israel waits in terror, but by dawn its enemies are dead. This is the just reward of those who plunder and destroy the people of God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 18, 1, 'Destruction is certain for the land of Ethiopia, which lies at the headwaters of the Nile. Its winged sailboats glide along the river,', 'NLT'),
(27, 18, 2, 'and ambassadors are sent in fast boats down the Nile. Go home, swift messengers! Take a message to your land divided by rivers, to your tall, smooth-skinned people, who are feared far and wide for their conquests and destruction.', 'NLT');
